// echo.su — first userspace utility.
//
// Yantra's smallest possible v0 of "command-line file access" milestone:
// take an input axon, return it unchanged. The kernel router and the
// orchestrator handle the actual stdin/stdout routing through axon
// channels declared in echo.toml.
//
// This is intentionally trivial. The point is not the computation —
// it's that we have a SHIPPABLE userspace utility under apps/, with
// its own manifest, admitted by the kernel just like any other
// service, accessed via axon-passing rather than any conventional
// stdin/stdout file descriptor. When real Sutra string + IO + FS
// vocabulary matures (per todo.md § 2), the utility list grows from
// here. echo is the bottom of that ladder.
//
// The bound key "stdin_text" is what the producer (whoever invokes
// echo from the host side) puts the input under; the read key is
// the same — `axon_item(input, "stdin_text")` extracts and returns
// the value. The orchestrator's job is to route the result on
// echo's R_stdout output role, where a downstream stdout sink
// (eventually) consumes it.

function vector on_axon(vector input_axon) {
    Axon out;
    out.add("stdout_text", axon_item(input_axon, "stdin_text"));
    return out;
}
